defaultWritten evidence submitted by the defaultIndustrial Communities Alliancedefault&#xa0;defaultIndustrial Communities Alliancedefault&#xa0;defaultThe Industrial Communities Alliance is the all-party 
defaultassociation of local authorities in the industrial areas of England, Scotland and Wales.  The Alliance was formed in 2007 by the merger of longer-standing associations dating back to the 1980s.  The Alliance
default works with the Westminster government, the devol
defaultved administrations and the EU to deliver
default policies and funding 
defaultthat
default support economic and social regeneration.  Some 60 local authorities are currently members.
default&#xa0;
defaultWelfare reform has been a regular topic of discussion at regional and national meetings of the 
defaultAlliance.  The present submission draws on these discussions and on published academic evidenc
defaulte to illustrate the
default impact 
defaultthat 
defaultwelfare reform in general, and reform to housing benefits in particular, is having in much of older industrial Britain.  The submi
defaultssion was prepared by staff in the National Secretariat and endorsed by the Alliance Executive, comprising senior elected members from around the country.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultContextdefault&#xa0;defaultBritain’s older industrial areas include some of the most economically deprived parts of t
defaulthe UK.  Over many years, substantial parts of Scotland, Wales and the North of England, and even some areas further south, have seen the decline of the industries on which their economies and communities were once based.  Coal, steel, shipbuilding and text
defaultiles, for example, have now disappeared entirely from some places and survive only on a much diminished scale in others.  This has cast a long shadow over economic and social well-being.  Reg
defaulteneration efforts have brought
default new jobs, but rarely on a sufficie
defaultnt scale
default to offset previous job losses.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe result is that Britain’s older industrial areas mostly suffer from high levels of worklessness.  Even in the years prior to the 2008 recession, they remained a long way off ful
defaultl employment.  The worklessness
default is 
defaultfar more extensive than just conventional ‘un
defaultemployment’.  For example,
default one of the long-term consequences of a weak demand for labour 
defaultin older industrial Britain 
defaulthas been that very large numbers of men and women with health problems or disabilities have en
defaultded up 
defaultparked outside of the labour market on incapacity benefits.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe consequence is
default that individuals
default are more likely to be out-of-work on benefits in older industrial Britain than in more prosperous local economies.  Because of lower wages for those in 
defaultwork, they are also more likely to draw on in-work benefits.
default&#xa0;
defaultWelfare reform
default te
defaultnds to be discussed with little
default reference to its impact in specific places up and down the country.  However, because benefit claimant rates va
defaultry so much across Britain,
default the pla
defaultces where claimants are concentrated – such as older industrial areas – are 
defaultclearly 
defaultmost exposed to financial losses.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultCase study: under-occupation of social housing (‘bedroom tax’)default&#xa0;
defaultTo illustrate the disproportionate impact of welfa
defaultre reform
default on olde
defaultr 
defaultindustrial areas
default it is worth looking at the new under-occupation rules governing support for housing costs in 
defaultthe social rented sector, generally
default known as the ‘bedroom tax’.  The rules on under-occupation are of course the same across the who
defaultle country but
default the impact differs
default from place to place for two 
defaultmain 
defaultreasons.
default&#xa0;
defaultFirst, the 
defaultshare of the housing stock 
defaultin the social rented sector
default varies a great deal across the country.  This often reflect
defaults
default complex historical reasons – the aftermath of the redevelopment of slum housing for example, and t
defaulthe differing priority that
default authorities once attached to building council houses.  Older industrial Britain, with a legacy of slum clearance and a tradit
defaultion o
defaultf municipal activism,
default has some of the highest proportions of social housing.
default&#xa0;
defaultSecond, the 
defaultproportion of working-age households who claim Housing Benefit
default varies according to the scale of worklessness and the extent of low wages.  Older industrial Britain 
defaultis
default among the places where the claimant rate is highest.
default&#xa0;
defaultFigure 1 shows the estimated impact of the ‘bedroom tax’ by district across the whole of Great Britain.  The figures here are taken from a report by Sheffield Hallam University
default, publis
defaulthed earlier in 2
default013, and are
default ultimately rooted in the Treasury’s own estimates of the financial savings and in DWP benefits data for 
defaultlocal areas.  T
defaulthe map shows the 
defaultannual 
defaultfinancial loss 
defaultper adult of working age – i.e. averaging the financial loss across the whole working
default age population of each area, inclu
defaultding non-claimants
default.  This is the best measure of the intensity of the financial ‘hit’ in each part of the country.
default&#xa0;
defaultAnyone familiar with the economic geo
defaultgraphy of Britain will see that 
defaultthe areas hit hardest by the ‘bedroo
defaultm tax’
default include
default the industrial areas of northern England, the Welsh Valleys, the Birmingham and Glasgow areas and a number of inner London boroughs.  By contrast, substantial parts of the south and east of England outside London are relatively lightly affec
defaultted.
