default&#xa0;
defaultOther reforms to housing supportdefault&#xa0;
defaultT
defaulthe evidence on the other elements
default of support for housing costs 
defaultconfirms an
default uneven impact across the country, though not always in 
defaultquite 
defaultthe same way as for the ‘bedroom tax’.  The Sheffield Hallam study, for example, indicates that the
default household benefit cap
default impact
defaults
default to a major extent 
defaultonly in London, where
default rent levels 
defaulthave hithert
defaulto driven up Housing Benefit entitlement
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe reforms to
default Local Housing Allowanc
defaulte
default, 
defaultwhich apply to the private-
defaultrented sector
default,
default impact on London because of high rent levels but quite a number of older industrial areas in the North West, Yorkshire and North Eas
defaultt are also badly affected because of the high proporti
defaulton of tenants
default out-of-work or on low wages.
default  There are reports
default that in some places private landlords have become nervous about letting or re-letting to Housing Benefit claimants and that this is feeding 
defaultthrough to levels of homelessness.  Indeed, government figures show that the proportion of households citing loss of a private tenancy as the trigger for their homelessness is 
defaultr
defaultis
defaulti
defaultng and now at an all-time high.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe impacts of the reforms to Council Tax 
defaultBenefit are complex.  It might have been expected that older industrial areas would be hit hard because of hig
defaulth worklessness
default.  In the event, the devolved administrations and a number of English local authorities, such County Durham and Northumberland, have
default chosen not to pass on the reduction in government grant.  But as the Sheffield Hallam report shows, in the older industrial areas where the cut in government grant has been passed on in full the
default financial losses
default are among the largest in the country.
default&#xa0;
defaultLook
defaulting a little further ah
defaultead, there are
default worries that the intention to pay the ‘rent’ component of Universal Credit to claimants rather than direct to landlords, and to do so on a monthly rather than for
defaulttnightly basis, will have damaging
default repercussions for hou
defaultsing associations and local councils.  The fear is that the financial pressures on tenants will mean that rent
defaults go unpaid and arrears
default develop.  Since social landlords borrow against their anticipated income stream, this 
defaultalso 
defaulthas potential knock-on conseque
defaultnces for 
defaultthe volume of 
defaultnew building.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe cumulative impact odefaultn householdsdefault&#xa0;
