defaultAlthough for very specific reasons a 
defaultseaside town (Blackpool) and an inner London borough (Westminster) top this list, a careful reading of the other authorities in the top 50 shows that around two-thirds are ‘older industrial areas’.  By contrast, the 20 districts least impacted by the welfa
defaultre reforms, also shown in the table, are all in southern and eastern England outside London.  The disparities are very large – a factor of nearly four-to-one between the extremes, and in excess of two-to-one in all other cases on this table.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultConcluding rdefaultemarksdefault&#xa0;defaultReforms to housing benefits, such as the introduction of the ‘bedroom tax’, will in most cases widen the divides in prosperity between the best and worst local economies across Britain.  The current welfare reforms, taken as a whole, also have this
default impact.  Britain’s older industrial areas are especially exposed to losses of benefit income.
default&#xa0;
defaultMinisters argue that one of the main effects of the welfare reforms will be to increase the financial incentive to work, and that because more people will look 
defaultfor work, more people will find work.  That work incentives for many will increase is not in dispute.  However, the Industrial Communities Alliance and its member authorities do not share the view that the welfare reforms will raise the overall level of em
defaultployment.  Some benefit claimants will intensify their job search, and some will find work, but in Britain’s weaker local economies, where there remains a shortfall in job opportunities, this will mostly be at the expense of other jobseekers.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the view 
defaultof the Alliance, the key to reducing the number of working-age benefit claimants is 
defaultregional and local economic growth
default.  In practice, by reducing household incomes and local spending power in older industrial Britain, the current welfare reforms are likely
default to have precisely the opposite effect.
